WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.425
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.425 --> 00:00:04.365
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.365 --> 00:00:06.790
[CLICKING]

00:00:09.533 --> 00:00:11.700
NANCY KANWISHER: So we're
talking about navigation--

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:13.590
how you know where
you are and how

00:00:13.590 --> 00:00:16.680
you can get from here to
wherever else you want to go.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.920
And last time we talked about
just the general problems that

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.140
arise in navigation,
and we talked

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:24.690
about the parahippocampal
place area

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:26.970
and other parts
of the brain that

00:00:26.970 --> 00:00:28.530
are involved in navigation.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:30.130
So today we're going
to continue that,

00:00:30.130 --> 00:00:32.850
but we're going to talk more
about the actual populations

00:00:32.850 --> 00:00:35.670
of neurons in your head that
are involved in doing this.

00:00:35.670 --> 00:00:37.590
And we'll talk about
a particular aspect

00:00:37.590 --> 00:00:40.710
of the problem of navigation,
which is called reorientation.

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:43.050
That is what happens when
you lose your bearings,

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:45.120
and you need to figure
out where you are again.

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:50.130
Reset your internal
map of where you are.

00:00:50.130 --> 00:00:52.020
And then we'll
talk about the idea

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:53.760
that this whole
system for navigation,

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:57.300
cool as it is and fascinating
as navigation itself is,

00:00:57.300 --> 00:01:00.630
is even more interesting because
there's increasing evidence

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:02.670
that we use that
same system for lots

00:01:02.670 --> 00:01:05.190
of other aspects of
high level cognition

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:08.010
that have nothing to
do with space per se.

00:01:08.010 --> 00:01:10.560
OK that's-- and then we'll
have a quiz, a short quiz.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:11.550
That's the agenda.

00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:12.130
Here we go.

00:01:12.130 --> 00:01:15.270
So the basic problems
of navigation are, one,

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:16.470
where am I?

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:20.950
And two, how do I get from here
to wherever else I want to go?

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:23.910
And as I mentioned last time,
we can break down each of these

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:25.920
into a bunch of
different components

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:27.520
and facets of that question.

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:29.820
So when we want to
know where we are,

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:33.220
that can involve recognizing
a familiar location.

00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:35.760
So if you see a photograph
or you were plunked down

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:38.775
spontaneously in an
environment someplace you know,

00:01:38.775 --> 00:01:41.038
you would visually recognize
it, and that would be

00:01:41.038 --> 00:01:42.330
one way to know where you were.

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:45.010
Like, this is my living room.

00:01:45.010 --> 00:01:46.793
Even if that location
is unfamiliar

00:01:46.793 --> 00:01:48.210
and you're plunked
down at random,

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:50.820
you still have some idea of
what kind of a place this is.

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:52.460
Am I in a natural environment?

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:53.470
An urban environment?

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:54.240
Am I inside?

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:57.520
Am I outside, et cetera?

00:01:57.520 --> 00:01:59.250
And finally, you
would have some sense

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:03.870
of where you are with respect
to the immediate bounding

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:05.730
structures in your
immediate environment.

00:02:05.730 --> 00:02:07.950
Like, for example, where
you are in this room.

00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:09.570
As I'm talking to
you right now, I'm

00:02:09.570 --> 00:02:12.570
aware that there's
a wall behind me.

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:16.740
That kind of immediate
spatial location.

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:18.477
In terms of questions
that arise when

00:02:18.477 --> 00:02:21.060
we have to figure out how do we
get from here to wherever else

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:23.940
we want to go.

00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:27.613
If you can directly see
or hear your destination,

00:02:27.613 --> 00:02:29.280
then you have the
simplest possible kind

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:31.140
of navigation strategy.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:33.150
You just go toward that thing.

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:36.150
OK, that's called beaconing, and
it's like the minimalist case.

00:02:36.150 --> 00:02:39.750
Works great if you can see
or hear your destination.

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:43.020
But when you can't,
you need to know,

00:02:43.020 --> 00:02:46.290
where am I in my
broader understanding

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:49.410
of the layout of my environment
and where is my goal.

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:52.168
And for that, you need a
mental map of your environment,

00:02:52.168 --> 00:02:53.710
and we'll talk more
about that today.

00:02:53.710 --> 00:02:55.740
That's why it's in red.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:57.847
You also need to know
your current heading

00:02:57.847 --> 00:02:58.680
in that environment.

00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:00.930
It's not enough to know
in my map of the world,

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:02.475
I am here with a dot.

00:03:02.475 --> 00:03:03.960
You needs to know
which way you're

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:06.540
facing in that map
of the world in order

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.810
to plan your navigation, and
we'll talk about that too.

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:12.940
We also need to know what
routes are possible from here.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:15.710
So I may want to go over to
Stata and get a cup of coffee.

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:16.710
But I can't go this way.

00:03:16.710 --> 00:03:19.410
I've got to go around because
I can't go through that glass.

00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:23.340
OK, and so finally, this
whole magnificent system

00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:25.260
that enables us to
process all this stuff

00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:26.970
works pretty impressively.

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:29.340
But every once in a while,
something will go wrong,

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.550
and it will get the wrong
signal, and then we're lost.

00:03:32.550 --> 00:03:34.920
And so then we need a way
to regain our bearings,

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.140
and we'll talk about that too.

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:40.650
So last time I talked about
a bunch of brain regions

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:43.020
that are implicated
in perceiving scenes

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:44.430
and in navigation.

00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:46.680
We talked about the
parahippocampal place area

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:50.730
right here and this region over
here, formerly known as TOS,

00:03:50.730 --> 00:03:51.780
now known as OPA.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:53.280
You don't need to
remember all that.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.290
It's the bit that's out
on the lateral surface

00:03:55.290 --> 00:03:57.360
that we can zap
because it's out there.

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.090
And both of those regions
seem to be involved broadly

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:04.000
in perceiving the shape
of space around you.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.810
We also talked a bit about
retrosplenial cortex,

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:08.573
that region that's
hiding in the sulcus

00:04:08.573 --> 00:04:10.740
here that you can see better
when you mathematically

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:12.840
unfold the sulcus, there it is.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:14.970
Responds more to
scenes than objects.

00:04:14.970 --> 00:04:17.579
And that region seems to
be involved in something

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:19.890
like getting your bearings--
that is the location

00:04:19.890 --> 00:04:22.980
and orientation of where
you are with respect

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:25.390
to your cognitive
map and environment.

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:27.330
OK, so to make that
a little more vivid,

00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:29.880
I gave you one description
of a patient before,

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:31.950
but here's from another study.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:36.370
Patients with damage to
retrosplenial cortex--

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:38.160
so here's from a
recent article--

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:41.100
in every case, the
patient with this damage

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:44.490
was able to recognize landmarks
in their neighborhoods

00:04:44.490 --> 00:04:46.380
and retained a sense
of familiarity.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:47.370
I know that place.

00:04:47.370 --> 00:04:50.820
That's the coffee shop
five blocks from my house.

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:53.370
But despite that,
none of those patients

00:04:53.370 --> 00:04:56.310
were able to find their way
in familiar environments,

00:04:56.310 --> 00:04:59.040
and all but one were
unable to learn new routes.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.120
So they can recognize the visual
form of a particular place,

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:04.710
but they don't know
how to relate that

00:05:04.710 --> 00:05:06.540
to their cognitive
map of the world

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:11.160
and therefore plan
a route from there.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:14.310
OK, so the part
that I only alluded

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:17.820
to at the end-- yes, question?

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.180
AUDIENCE: OK, is the
retrosplenial cortex

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:23.727
the home to the cognitive
maps, or is it--

00:05:23.727 --> 00:05:25.060
NANCY KANWISHER: Great question.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:26.250
We don't exactly know.

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:29.760
The typical story is that
the home of the cognitive map

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:32.610
is the hippocampus, which
we're about to talk about next

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:33.960
for reasons I will tell you.

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:37.718
But all of this is a very
active area of research.

00:05:37.718 --> 00:05:39.510
It kills me every time
I do these lectures.

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:41.160
I look at my old
notes, and I think

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.070
here are these 10
other awesome studies,

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:45.570
and then I try to fit them in,
and then they just don't fit.

00:05:45.570 --> 00:05:47.153
So actually one
question I want to ask

00:05:47.153 --> 00:05:50.040
you guys after this lecture
is, should I in future,

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:52.490
either later in this course
or in future courses,

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:54.990
allocate even more time, or do
you guys feel like OK, enough

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:56.100
already with navigation.

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:57.808
But I just think it's
the coolest system.

00:05:57.808 --> 00:06:00.557
So there's lots of
work exactly trying

00:06:00.557 --> 00:06:01.890
to answer that kind of question.

00:06:01.890 --> 00:06:04.650
And I'll give you
a current snapshot

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:06.690
of the approximate
state, but all of this

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:12.060
is in flux and very much
actively investigated.

00:06:12.060 --> 00:06:16.230
OK, so cognitive map,
what do we mean by that?

00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:19.890
Just to remind you of this
classic study from the 1940s

00:06:19.890 --> 00:06:23.248
in rats, where the rat,
when they learned this route

00:06:23.248 --> 00:06:25.290
and then went up here and
found their gold block,

00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:27.248
the rat immediately comes
out and goes straight

00:06:27.248 --> 00:06:28.050
toward the goal.

00:06:28.050 --> 00:06:30.750
Telling you they've learned
something much more interesting

00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:33.630
than the series of left and
right turns to get to the goal.

00:06:33.630 --> 00:06:37.170
They must have done something
much more like actually learned

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.165
the layout of space and the
relative position of that goal

00:06:40.165 --> 00:06:41.790
so they could come
up with a new vector

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:44.730
to get there when the
original route was blocked.

00:06:44.730 --> 00:06:48.240
OK, and you guys
can do this too.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.930
When your route is blocked,
you come up with a novel route.

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:55.830
And you do that by having some
knowledge of your environment,

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:58.590
something tantamount
to that in your head,

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:00.240
some version of that.

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:03.030
And further, you know
where you are in that map.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:06.540
Like right now, you
know where you are.

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:08.010
Now here's the cool thing--

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:10.440
specific neurons
in your hippocampus

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:16.560
right now are firing telling
you that you are right there.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:19.540
So these neurons are
called place cells,

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:20.850
and this is what they do.

00:07:20.850 --> 00:07:23.580
OK, so I'll be a place
cell, or rather what I'll do

00:07:23.580 --> 00:07:27.000
is I will act out the
activity of a place cell

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.610
by a series of clicks I
will make as I walk around.

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:32.740
So imagine there's an
electrode in my hippocampus,

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:35.400
and you are hearing the
activity of a single neuron

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:37.660
in my hippocampus
as I walk around.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:39.150
And here's what it would do.

00:07:39.150 --> 00:07:40.560
You'd hear background firing.

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:43.920
So it's going to go click,
click, click, click, click.

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:45.392
Noisy background firing.

00:07:45.392 --> 00:07:47.100
Click, click, click,
click, click, click,

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:47.900
click, click, click, click.

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:49.300
Click, click, click,
click, click, click, click,

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:50.700
click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:52.300
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click,

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:53.700
click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:55.300
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:57.600
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:58.540
OK, I'm not going
to go down there.

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:00.140
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:01.540
Click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:03.140
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:04.540
Click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:06.140
Click, click, click, click,
click, click, click, click,

00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:08.140
click, click, click,
click, click, click, click.

00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:10.650
So that's one neuron
that fires only when I'm

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:12.780
right over there, that place.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.940
It's not where I'm
facing over there.

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:17.040
It's not what I'm
looking at particularly.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:19.740
It's when I'm right there.

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:22.180
OK, that's a place cell.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:25.500
And so there's lots of place
cells in your hippocampus

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:27.690
that do that, and they do
it for different locations

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:29.790
in your environment.

00:08:29.790 --> 00:08:31.950
And all of this was first
worked out, of course,

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:34.320
in rodents, who
were running around

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.809
who had electrodes
in their hippocampus,

00:08:36.809 --> 00:08:39.659
but where those electrodes were
connected with a loose tether

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:42.240
so that the rodent could move
around in their environment

00:08:42.240 --> 00:08:45.210
while recording from individual
neurons in the hippocampus.

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:46.930
OK, so that's the setup.

00:08:46.930 --> 00:08:49.680
And so I'm going to show you
a movie of an aerial view

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:52.650
of a rodent moving around--

00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:54.570
a rat moving around
in its environment.

00:08:54.570 --> 00:08:56.670
Can you see the
little rat there?

00:08:56.670 --> 00:08:59.310
And what's happening
is this video

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:02.220
is tracing out the rat's
path with the light gray.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:04.590
And every time that-- and
it's recording from one

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:08.550
neuron-- every time that neuron
fires, it makes a red dot.

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:10.440
So this is obviously sped up.

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:13.200
But as the rat moves
around in his environment,

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.930
you see an accumulation
like more firing

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:17.550
when the rat is right there.

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:19.515
It's not which direction
the rat is going

00:09:19.515 --> 00:09:20.640
through when he goes there.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.170
Just basically
whenever he passes

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:24.870
through that in any
direction, neurons

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:27.460
fire more than anywhere else.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:29.550
And then if we take
that and blur it,

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:33.270
as scientists like to do to
make nice idealized pictures,

00:09:33.270 --> 00:09:36.570
that is the place
cell for that neuron.

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:40.770
That is the place in
space that that animal has

00:09:40.770 --> 00:09:44.200
to be to make that neuron fire.

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:45.550
Yeah, question.

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:47.580
AUDIENCE: Is it one dimension?

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:51.540
I mean, can multiple places
be mapped to the same neuron?

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:53.040
NANCY KANWISHER:
That's complicated.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:56.190
In an immediate environment
like this, generally not.

00:09:56.190 --> 00:09:58.710
OK, I'll show you some
examples in a moment.

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:00.660
It's more complicated
if you follow

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:03.170
that cell when the animal
moves to a new location.

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:05.670
So let me say a few more things,
and then if it's not clear,

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:06.503
I'll take questions.

00:10:06.503 --> 00:10:09.090
Oops, we're going
to see that again.

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:12.810
OK, right so in answer
to Sasha's question, here

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:15.480
are a bunch of place cells
from a rodent exploring

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:17.110
the same environment.

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:19.860
So you might say, well,
there's a hotspot here

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:21.580
and a little sub one there.

