00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:51.090
So just to cash this
out, the place field

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:53.250
is the location in
space the animal

00:12:53.250 --> 00:12:56.610
has to be to make that
hippocampal cell fire.

00:12:56.610 --> 00:13:01.080
OK, so let's distinguish
that from a receptive

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:03.510
field in visual cortex,
which is a similar idea

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:04.620
but a different one.

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:06.690
A receptive field
and visual cortex

00:13:06.690 --> 00:13:08.670
is the location in
the visual field

00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:12.607
where a stimulus has to be
to make a visual neuron fire.

00:13:12.607 --> 00:13:14.190
Not where the animal
itself has to be,

00:13:14.190 --> 00:13:15.960
where the stimulus has to be.

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:17.950
So keep those ideas separate.

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:20.490
They're related but different.

00:13:20.490 --> 00:13:24.240
OK, so what about we and
rodents tend to go around mostly

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:26.250
on a 2D plane.

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:28.920
That is we have buildings
and trees and stuff.

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:30.640
We sometimes go
up in the z-axis,

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:33.330
but mostly we live
in a 2D plane,

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:35.320
but that's not true
of all animals.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:37.650
So recall the bat that
I mentioned last time.

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:42.210
These amazing flyers and
navigators who fly in 3D

00:13:42.210 --> 00:13:44.400
and complicated
trajectories and yet

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:47.250
have amazing abilities
to keep track

00:13:47.250 --> 00:13:51.750
of where they are over 30 to
50 miles that they fly at night

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:54.600
and even as they change
their orientation.

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:57.960
Well, it turns out that in
the hippocampus of bats,

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:03.880
there's a bunch of work where
people have put remote--

00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:06.300
what do you call these
things-- recording devices

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:09.900
on bats, where you can
remotely record neural activity

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:13.530
in the hippocampus as
the bat flies around.

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:16.290
And it turns out that
bats have place cells too,

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:19.670
and their place
cells, as they also

00:14:19.670 --> 00:14:22.170
can do this in a lab environment
where they're flying around

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:25.050
and you keep track of their
location with cameras.

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:28.200
So you know exactly where
they are in 3D space.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:30.840
And it turns out that
place cells in bats

00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:32.730
are three dimensional
because bats live

00:14:32.730 --> 00:14:34.470
in a three dimensional world.

00:14:34.470 --> 00:14:38.880
So whereas rodent-- these would
be a bunch of schematized place

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:43.200
cells for different
hippocampal cells in a rodent,

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:48.150
these are different place cells
for different hippocampal cells

00:14:48.150 --> 00:14:49.320
in a bat.

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:49.950
Make sense?

00:14:49.950 --> 00:14:50.730
Bats need this.

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:52.470
They need to know--
not making sense?

00:14:52.470 --> 00:14:54.990
OK, so the bat is moving
around in three dimensions.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:57.690
Its place field isn't just
like the one I did there.

00:14:57.690 --> 00:14:59.760
I can't act this out
because I can't fly,

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:03.150
but that place cell might
fire over in that location.

00:15:03.150 --> 00:15:06.360
But then if the bat flew
directly above it, it wouldn't.

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:07.945
So it's got three dimensions.

00:15:07.945 --> 00:15:08.445
OK.

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:15.590
OK, so I said before
that I had one of those,

00:15:15.590 --> 00:15:16.610
and I acted it out.

00:15:16.610 --> 00:15:18.770
But what's the
evidence for that?

00:15:18.770 --> 00:15:23.925
The evidence in humans came way
after the evidence in rodents.

00:15:23.925 --> 00:15:25.550
Because as you can
imagine, it's harder

00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:28.040
to arrange to record
from individual neurons

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:30.110
in human hippocampus.

00:15:30.110 --> 00:15:33.290
Nonetheless, as I've
mentioned a few times

00:15:33.290 --> 00:15:35.330
there are occasional
opportunities

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:37.730
where a neurosurgeon
has stuck an electrode

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:41.030
in an interesting part of the
brain for clinical reasons,

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:42.830
and the patient and
the neurosurgeon

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:46.718
are nice enough to let
scientists collect data.

00:15:46.718 --> 00:15:49.010
So I'm going to show you a
really gross bloody picture.

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:50.990
If that's going to bother
you, just look away.

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:55.250
OK, so this is neurosurgery.

00:15:55.250 --> 00:15:58.880
You take the skull off,
you take the dura off.

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:01.310
That's the direct
surface of the brain.

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:03.140
The neurosurgeons
stick electrodes

00:16:03.140 --> 00:16:04.290
right on top of there.

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:07.280
And in this case, they put
them deep inside the brain.

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:08.640
OK, the gross pictures are gone.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:13.350
We have just a nice
clean X-ray here.

00:16:13.350 --> 00:16:17.510
So in these cases,
this is a patient

00:16:17.510 --> 00:16:20.090
who's got an electrode
sticking straight

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:22.490
into the brain from
the surface straight

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:25.010
down n to the hippocampus.

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:29.660
OK, kind of horrifying,
but sometimes clinically

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:30.680
called for.

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:32.970
Seizures very often
start in the hippocampus,

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:37.670
so this is a commonplace for
clinicians to put electrodes.

00:16:37.670 --> 00:16:40.760
And so what would you do
if you had a patient who

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:43.400
was willing to do your short
experiment while hanging out

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:46.010
in the hospital waiting to
have a seizure with electrodes

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:47.150
in their hippocampus?

00:16:47.150 --> 00:16:51.320
Well, you'd have them
play a little game

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:54.650
in a virtual space in some kind
of-- you don't even need VR.

00:16:54.650 --> 00:16:57.555
You can use a pretty
cheesy little video game,

00:16:57.555 --> 00:16:59.180
and I'm sure this
one was quite cheesy.

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:01.670
This study was
done back in 2003.

00:17:01.670 --> 00:17:05.720
So they had patients navigate
through a space-- this

00:17:05.720 --> 00:17:07.430
is an aerial view of the space.

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:08.810
The patients didn't see that.

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:12.440
They saw this front view,
and they navigated around

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:14.460
with the joystick in that space.

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:19.053
And there were three visually
recognizable locations

00:17:19.053 --> 00:17:20.720
in that space, and
they had to do things

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:23.089
to go from one
location to another.

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:25.130
OK, details don't really matter.

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:28.850
So all the while,
Ekstrom and colleagues

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:31.100
are recording from
individual neurons

00:17:31.100 --> 00:17:33.740
in this patient's hippocampus.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:37.050
OK, so here's an
example of a place cell.

00:17:37.050 --> 00:17:39.890
So this is a diagram of the
space I just showed you,

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:43.730
with those three recognizable
locations and other locations

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:46.130
that the patient could
virtually navigate through

00:17:46.130 --> 00:17:47.090
with the joystick.

00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:49.280
The red lines are the
patient's trajectory

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:51.470
as they moved around
in that space.

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:53.930
And the colors
within each square

00:17:53.930 --> 00:17:59.150
are the average firing rate
when the patient navigated

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:01.230
through that location.

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:04.850
And so this is the place
field of that individual cell

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:07.310
in this patient's brain as
they went through this space.

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:10.190
Because the firing rate
there was around five hertz

00:18:10.190 --> 00:18:12.710
compared to three hertz
for some other locations

00:18:12.710 --> 00:18:15.050
and mostly lower than that.

00:18:15.050 --> 00:18:16.200
OK, does that make sense?

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:18.080
So just like the
rodent experiment,

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:21.950
but it's a person with a
joystick looking at this space

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:24.410
as they go through this
virtual environment,

00:18:24.410 --> 00:18:27.480
and we're mapping out their
place fields like that.

00:18:27.480 --> 00:18:30.080
OK, so that shows
that humans have

00:18:30.080 --> 00:18:31.790
place fields in
their hippocampus

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:33.560
just as rodents and bats do.

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:34.370
Yeah?

00:18:34.370 --> 00:18:38.863
AUDIENCE: Well, this is
independent of landmarks?

00:18:38.863 --> 00:18:41.030
NANCY KANWISHER: That's a
very complicated question.

00:18:41.030 --> 00:18:43.220
This patient had
access to landmarks.

00:18:43.220 --> 00:18:45.330
They are seeing as
they go through.

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:47.810
So one could ask, for
example, if you did it

00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:50.600
with your eyes closed and you
had to go by dead reckoning

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:52.280
remembering the
left and right turns

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:53.900
you had in a
familiar environment,

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:56.390
how well could these things
go, they would go for at least

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:57.380
a while.

00:18:57.380 --> 00:18:59.330
They'd probably go
for longer in rodents

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:01.910
because rodents are more
accustomed to navigating

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:02.450
in the dark.

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:06.590
And they rely less on visual
cues and more on other cues.

00:19:06.590 --> 00:19:11.390
But yeah, place cells aren't
just visually responsive.

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:14.330
So if we had, for
example, if we set up

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:18.680
a distinctive sound
source in this corner

00:19:18.680 --> 00:19:21.350
of the room and a
different-- like say somebody

00:19:21.350 --> 00:19:26.210
was singing quietly over here,
and we tied a dog over there

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:27.800
who was barking.

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.930
And you walked around in
this room with your eyes

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:33.892
closed, you'd have a good way
to keep track of your bearings

00:19:33.892 --> 00:19:36.350
as you moved around because
you'd know that the singing was

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:38.808
coming from here and the dog
barking was coming from there.

00:19:38.808 --> 00:19:40.212
You wouldn't be seeing anything.

00:19:40.212 --> 00:19:42.170
Your eyes would be closed,
but your place cells

00:19:42.170 --> 00:19:43.600
would work pretty well.

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:45.620
OK, so whenever
you have some basis

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:48.350
for knowing where you are,
no matter what modality

00:19:48.350 --> 00:19:49.640
is telling you that--

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:52.070
and usually it's
many modalities--

00:19:52.070 --> 00:19:53.300
those place cells will go.

00:19:55.910 --> 00:19:57.785
OK, so humans have
these things too.

00:19:57.785 --> 00:20:00.035
So you can think of the place
cell as the kind of "you

00:20:00.035 --> 00:20:03.810
are here" system that is the
whole set of place cells.

00:20:03.810 --> 00:20:05.480
Any one place will
only tell you are you

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:07.560
in this particular
location or not.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:09.080
But you have a
whole array of them,

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:12.320
then collectively, that
whole representation

00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:14.300
across all of those
neurons can tell you

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:17.630
where you are in your
familiar environment.

00:20:17.630 --> 00:20:22.590
OK, but if you want to not
just know where you are

00:20:22.590 --> 00:20:25.910
but you want to go
somewhere else, like there,

00:20:25.910 --> 00:20:28.430
you also need to know
your current heading

00:20:28.430 --> 00:20:31.760
as we discussed last time.

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:34.580
So it turns out that there
is a whole other batch

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:38.030
of cells that tell you
what way you're heading.

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:40.340
OK, these are called
head direction cells,

00:20:40.340 --> 00:20:42.980
also first studied in rodents.

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:45.770
And each head
direction cell responds

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:49.550
when that rodent is heading
in a particular direction,

00:20:49.550 --> 00:20:51.470
not in another direction.

00:20:51.470 --> 00:20:56.540
OK, so for example,
if we're mapping along

00:20:56.540 --> 00:20:58.362
the x-axis different
heading directions.

00:20:58.362 --> 00:21:00.320
So the rodent is facing
in different directions

00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:01.460
in his environment.

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.250
You map up the
whole 360 degrees,

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:06.170
this would be the
response of one cell

00:21:06.170 --> 00:21:08.780
as that rodent moves around.

00:21:08.780 --> 00:21:11.400
This one would be tuned to
this particular direction.

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:13.858
It would fire only when the
rodent was facing this way,

00:21:13.858 --> 00:21:15.650
not when it was facing
this way or this way

00:21:15.650 --> 00:21:18.410
or this way or this way.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:21.260
So does everybody get how
where you are in space

00:21:21.260 --> 00:21:25.520
is different-- that's not a
very good way to show this.

00:21:25.520 --> 00:21:28.460
Where you are in space
is different from where

00:21:28.460 --> 00:21:31.430
you're aimed and headed
in that location.

00:21:31.430 --> 00:21:35.750
OK, two orthogonal axes of
relevant to your location.

00:21:35.750 --> 00:21:36.755
Yeah?

00:21:36.755 --> 00:21:38.130
AUDIENCE: So this
isn't the angle

00:21:38.130 --> 00:21:39.980
of the head in respect
