01:10:10.773 --> 01:10:12.440
But yeah, these guys
are pretty careful,

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:15.170
and there are all these things--
there are many different ways

01:10:15.170 --> 01:10:21.080
in which people are
watching hippocampal neurons

01:10:21.080 --> 01:10:24.770
and decoding trajectories
from hippocampal neurons.

01:10:24.770 --> 01:10:27.020
You may have heard
about replay, which is

01:10:27.020 --> 01:10:28.780
a big thing in this department.

01:10:28.780 --> 01:10:30.770
Tonegawa and Wilson
labs study this,

01:10:30.770 --> 01:10:35.450
where you have a rodent moving
around in one trajectory

01:10:35.450 --> 01:10:36.950
during the day,
and then you record

01:10:36.950 --> 01:10:38.450
from those neurons
at night, and you

01:10:38.450 --> 01:10:41.270
see replay of the trajectories
that the rodent went through

01:10:41.270 --> 01:10:42.540
in the previous day.

01:10:42.540 --> 01:10:44.962
And so there you have to be
really careful to say, OK,

01:10:44.962 --> 01:10:46.670
there's a lot of data
and a lot of noise,

01:10:46.670 --> 01:10:48.295
and is this really
more than the noise?

01:10:48.295 --> 01:10:52.050
And it is, but it takes a lot of
statistical work to show that.

